Definition 1.3.2. Let $n\in{\mathbb{Z}}$; let $t$ be a $t$-structure on $\underline{C}$. 1. $\underline{C}^{t\geq n}$ (resp. $\underline{C}^{t\leq n}$) will denote $\underline{C}^{t\geq 0}[-n]$ (resp. $\underline{C}^{t\leq 0}[-n]$); $\underline{C}^{t=0}=\underline{C}^{t\geq 0}\cap\underline{C}^{t\leq 0}$. 2. ${\underline{Ht}}$ will be the full subcategory of $\underline{C}$ whose object class is $\underline{C}^{t=0}$. 3. We will say that $t$ is right non-degenerate if $\cap_{i\in{\mathbb{Z}}}\underline{C}^{t\geq i}=\{0\}$. We will say that $t$ is (just) non-degenerate if we also have $\cap_{i\in{\mathbb{Z}}}\underline{C}^{t\leq i}=\{0\}$. 4. We will say that $t$ is bounded above if $\underline{C}=\cup_{i\in{\mathbb{Z}}}\underline{C}^{t\leq i}$.
Definition 4.1.1. For a sequence of objects $Y_{i}$ of $\underline{C}$ for $i\geq 0$ and maps $\phi_{i}:Y_{i}\to Y_{i+1}$ we consider the morphism $a:\oplus\operatorname{id}_{Y_{i}}\bigoplus\oplus(-\phi_{i}):D\to D$ (we can define it since its $i$-th component can be easily factorized as the composition $Y_{i}\to Y_{i}\bigoplus Y_{i+1}\to D$). Denote a cone of $a$ by $Y$; $\operatorname{\operatorname{Cone}}(\phi_{i})$ will be denoted by $Z_{i+1}$ and we set $Z_{0}=Y_{0}$. We will write $Y=\operatorname{\varinjlim}Y_{i}$ and call $Y$ a homotopy colimit of $Y_{i}$ (we will not consider any other homotopy colimits in this paper).
Definition 5.2.1. Let $\underline{C}^{\prime}$ be a triangulated category. 1. We will call a (covariant) bi-functor $\Phi:\underline{C}^{op}\times\underline{C}^{\prime}\to\underline{A}$ a duality if it is bi-additive, homological with respect to both arguments, and is equipped with a (bi)natural bi-additive transformation $\Phi(A,Y)\cong\Phi(A[1],Y[1])$. 2. Suppose that $\underline{C}$ is endowed with a torsion pair $s=(\mathcal{LO},\mathcal{RO})$ and $\underline{C}^{\prime}$ is endowed with a torsion pair $s^{\prime}=(\mathcal{LO}^{\prime},\mathcal{RO}^{\prime})$. Then we will say that $s$ is (left) orthogonal to $s^{\prime}$ with respect to $\Phi$ (or just left $\Phi$-orthogonal to it) if the following orthogonality condition is fulfilled: $\Phi(X,Y)=0$ whenever $X\in\mathcal{LO}$ and $Y\in\mathcal{LO}^{\prime}$ or if $X\in\mathcal{RO}$ and $Y\in\mathcal{RO}^{\prime}$. 3. Suppose that $\underline{C}$ is endowed with a weight structure $w$, $\underline{C}^{\prime}$ is endowed with a $t$-structure $t$. Then we will say that $w$ is (left) orthogonal to $t$ with respect to $\Phi$ if the following condition is fulfilled: $\Phi(X,Y)=0$ if $X\in\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}$ and $Y\in\underline{C}^{\prime t\geq 1}$ or if $X\in\underline{C}_{w\leq 0}$ and $Y\in\underline{C}^{\prime t\leq-1}$. 4. We will say that $\Phi$ is nice if for any distinguished triangles $T=A\stackrel{{\scriptstyle l}}{{\to}}B\stackrel{{\scriptstyle m}}{{\to}}C% \stackrel{{\scriptstyle n}}{{\to}}A[1]$ in $\underline{C}$ and $X\stackrel{{\scriptstyle f}}{{\to}}Y\stackrel{{\scriptstyle g}}{{\to}}Z% \stackrel{{\scriptstyle h}}{{\to}}X[1]$ in $\underline{C}^{\prime}$ we have the following: the natural morphism $p$: $\begin{gathered}\displaystyle\operatorname{\operatorname{Ker}}(\Phi(A,X)% \bigoplus\Phi(B,Y)\bigoplus\Phi(C,Z))\\ \displaystyle\xrightarrow{\begin{pmatrix}\Phi(A,-)(f)&-\Phi(-,Y)(l)&0\\ 0&g(B)&-\Phi(-,Z)(m)\\ -\Phi(-,X)([-1](n))&0&\Phi(C,-)(h)\end{pmatrix}}\\ \displaystyle(\Phi(A,Y)\bigoplus\Phi(B,Z)\bigoplus\Phi(C[-1],X))\stackrel{{% \scriptstyle p}}{{\to}}\operatorname{\operatorname{Ker}}((\Phi(A,X)\bigoplus% \Phi(B,Y))\\ \displaystyle\xrightarrow{\Phi(A,-)(f)\oplus-\Phi(-,Y)(l)}\Phi(A,Y))\end{gathered}$ is epimorphic.
Definition 2.4.1. Let $H$ be a cohomological functor from $\underline{C}$ into an abelian category $\underline{A}$; assume that $\underline{C}$ is endowed with a weight structure $w$ and $n\in{\mathbb{Z}}$. We define the virtual $t$-truncation functors $\tau^{\geq-n}(H)$ (resp. $\tau^{\leq-n}(H)$) by the correspondence $M\mapsto\operatorname{\operatorname{Im}}(H(w_{\leq n+1}M)\to H(w_{\leq n}M));$ (resp. $M\mapsto\operatorname{\operatorname{Im}}(H(w_{\geq n}M)\to H(w_{\geq n-1}M))$); here we take arbitrary choices of the corresponding weight truncations of $M$ and connect them using Proposition 2.1.4(6).
Definition 4.3.3. Let $\mathcal{P}$ be a subclass of $\operatorname{Obj}\underline{C}$, $h\in\underline{C}(M,N)$ (for some $M,N\in\operatorname{Obj}\underline{C}$). 1. We will say that $h$ is a $\mathcal{P}$-epic whenever for any $P\in\mathcal{P}$ the homomorphism $H^{P}(h)$ is surjective, i.e., if any $g\in\underline{C}(P,N)$ for $P\in\mathcal{P}$ factors through $h$. We will say that $h$ is $\mathcal{P}$-monic if all $H^{P}(h)$ are injective.48These definitions (along with the definition of $\mathcal{P}$-null morphisms) is taken from [Chr98]. 2. We will say that $h$ is a $\mathcal{P}$-approximation (of $N$) if it is a $\mathcal{P}$-epic and $M$ belongs to $\operatorname{Obj}\coprod\mathcal{P}$. 3. We will say that $\mathcal{P}$ is contravariantly finite (in $\underline{C}$) if for any $N\in\operatorname{Obj}\underline{C}$ there exists its $\mathcal{P}$-approximation.49Actually, the standard convention is to say that $\coprod\mathcal{P}$ is contravariantly finite if this condition is fulfilled; yet our version of this term is somewhat more convenient for the purposes of the current paper.
Definition 3.3.1. Let $\alpha$ be a regular infinite cardinal.33Recall that $\alpha$ is said to be regular if it cannot be presented as a sum of less then $\alpha$ cardinals that are less than $\alpha$. 1. An object $M$ of $\underline{C}$ is said to be $\alpha$-small if for any set of $N_{i}\in\operatorname{Obj}\underline{C}$ any morphism $M\to\coprod N_{i}$ factors through the coproduct of a subset of $\{N_{i}\}$ of cardinality less then $\alpha$. 2. We will say that a class $\mathcal{P}\subset\operatorname{Obj}\underline{C}$ is weakly perfect if the class of $\mathcal{P}$-null morphisms is closed with respect to countable coproducts (recall that $h$ is $\mathcal{P}$-null if for all $M\in\mathcal{P}$ we have $H^{M}(h)=0$; see Definition 1.2.2(5)). We will say that $\mathcal{P}$ is perfect if the class of $\mathcal{P}$-null morphisms is closed with respect to arbitrary coproducts. 3. We will say that $\underline{C}$ is perfectly generated if there exists a weakly perfect set $\mathcal{P}_{0}\subset\operatorname{Obj}\underline{C}$ that Hom-generates it. We will also say that $\underline{C}$ is $\alpha$-well generated (or just well generated) if (in addition) all elements of $\mathcal{P}_{0}$ are $\alpha$-small and $\mathcal{P}_{0}$ is perfect.
Definition 2.1.1. A couple of subclasses $\underline{C}_{w\leq 0},\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}\subset\operatorname{Obj}% \underline{C}$ will be said to define a weight structure $w$ for a triangulated category $\underline{C}$ if they satisfy the following conditions. (i) $\underline{C}_{w\leq 0}$ and $\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}$ are retraction-closed in $\underline{C}$ (i.e., contain all $\underline{C}$-retracts of their elements).22In [Bon10a] the axioms of a weight structure also required $\underline{C}_{w\leq 0}$ and $\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}$ to be additive. Yet this is not necessary; see Remark 1.2.3(4) of [BoS16]. (ii) Semi-invariance with respect to translations. $\underline{C}_{w\leq 0}\subset\underline{C}_{w\leq 0}[1]$ and $\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}[1]\subset\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}$. (iii) Orthogonality. $\underline{C}_{w\leq 0}\perp\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}[1]$. (iv) Weight decompositions. For any $M\in\operatorname{Obj}\underline{C}$ there exists a distinguished triangle $LM\to M\to RM{\to}LM[1]$ such that $LM\in\underline{C}_{w\leq 0}$ and $RM\in\underline{C}_{w\geq 0}[1]$.
Definition 4.8. We say that $(p,q)$ is an adjoint pair if it satisfies both the adjunction conditions in the beginning of this section and the additional exactness property above.
Definition 3.8. Suppose that $\mathcal{D}$ possesses an admissible pair, we say that $\mathcal{D}$ is admissible. Let $\mathcal{F}\in\mathcal{Z}^{\prime}_{\mathcal{D}}\mathcal{D}^{*}$. Define $HC_{\mathcal{D}}^{n}(\mathcal{F})=HC^{n}(C^{\bullet}(d,\mathcal{F}))$ for any admissible $(P,d)$.
Definition 4.29. We say that a $(\mathcal{C},\mathcal{D})$-bimodule category $\mathcal{N}$ is admissible if it is equivalent to $A_{\mathcal{D}}\mathbb{M}\text{d}$ as a right $\mathcal{D}$-module category and the resulting monoidal functor $\mathcal{C}\rightarrow\mathbb{B}\text{md}_{\mathcal{D}}A$ admits an exact right adjoint.
Definition 4.3. We say that a $2$-functor $F:\mathcal{B}\rightarrow\mathcal{B}^{\prime}$ is split if for all $x\in\mathcal{B}$ the functor $F_{x}:\mathcal{B}_{x}\rightarrow\mathcal{B}^{\prime}_{F(x)}$ has an exact right adjoint.
Definition 2.1. Let $A$ be a unital associative algebra in $\mathcal{C}$ and $\mathcal{F}$ a symmetric $2$-contratrace, then if $C^{n}=\mathcal{F}(A^{\otimes n+1})$ is the cocyclic object described above, we defined $HC^{n}_{old}(A,\mathcal{F})=HC^{n}(C^{\bullet}).$
Definition 4.6. Let $A$ be a unital associative algebra in $\mathcal{C}$ and $\mathcal{F}\in\mathcal{Z}^{\prime}_{\mathcal{C}}\mathcal{C}^{*}$ left exact. Then we obtain an $\mathcal{F}_{\bullet}\in\mathcal{Z}^{\prime}_{\mathbb{B}\text{md}_{\mathcal{C}% }}(\mathbb{B}\text{md}_{\mathcal{C}}^{*})$ and define the cyclic cohomology of $A$ with coefficients in $\mathcal{F}$ to be $HC^{n}(A,\mathcal{F}):=HC^{n}(A,\mathcal{F}_{\bullet})$ provided that $A$ is admissible as an object of $\mathbb{B}\text{md}_{\mathcal{C}}$. We often write $HC^{n}_{\mathcal{C}}(A,\mathcal{F})$ to emphasize the monoidal category.
Definition 3.1. Let $C^{n}=C^{n}(d,\mathcal{F})=\mathcal{F}(P^{\otimes n+1}).$ For $i=0,\cdots,n+1$ let $\delta_{i}^{\prime}:P^{\otimes n+2}\rightarrow P^{\otimes n+1}$ be given by $\delta_{i}^{\prime}=Id^{\otimes i}_{P}\otimes d\otimes Id_{P}^{\otimes n+1-i},$ and let $\delta_{i}=\mathcal{F}(\delta_{i}^{\prime}):C^{n}\rightarrow C^{n+1}.$ Define $\tau_{n}\in Aut(C^{n})$ via $\tau_{n}=\tau_{P,P^{\otimes n}}.$
Definition 3.5. We say that a pair $(P,d)$ with $d:P\rightarrow 1$ in $\mathcal{D}$ is admissible if $P^{\otimes 2}\xrightarrow{d\otimes Id-Id\otimes d}P\xrightarrow{d}1\rightarrow 0$ is exact and $P$ is projective.
Definition 4.14. We say that two monoidal categories $\mathcal{C}$ and $\mathcal{D}$ are $2$-Morita equivalent if $\mathbb{B}\text{md}_{\mathcal{C}}\simeq\mathbb{B}\text{md}_{\mathcal{D}}$. More precisely, $\mathcal{D}\simeq\mathbb{B}\text{md}_{\mathcal{C}}A$ for some unital associative $A\in\mathcal{C}$ and there is a unital associative algebra $S\in\mathbb{B}\text{md}_{\mathcal{C}}A$ such that $S$ is Morita equivalent to $1$ in $\mathcal{C}$, i.e., exist bimodules $P$ and $Q$ such that $P\otimes Q\simeq S$ and $Q\otimes_{S}P\simeq 1$ in $\mathcal{C}$.
Definition 4.1. We say that an object $x$ in $\mathcal{B}$ is admissible if $\mathcal{B}_{x}$ is admissible. Assuming that $x$ is admissible define the cyclic cohomology of $x$ with coefficients in $\mathcal{F}_{\bullet}\in\mathcal{Z}^{\prime}_{\mathcal{B}}\mathcal{B}^{*}$ as follows: $HC^{n}(x,\mathcal{F}_{\bullet})=HC^{n}_{\mathcal{B}_{x}}(\mathcal{F}_{x}).$
Definition 2.1. An operad $\mathscr{O}$ in $\mathcal{D}$ is a collection of objects $\{\mathscr{O}(n)\}_{n\geq 0}$ in $\mathcal{D}$ with a base point $\ast\in\mathscr{O}(0)$, a distinguished element $1\in\mathscr{O}(1)$, a right action of the symmetric group $\Sigma_{n}$ on $\mathscr{O}(n)$ for each $n\geq 0$, and structure maps $\gamma\colon\mathscr{O}(k)\otimes\mathscr{O}({j_{1}})\otimes\ldots\otimes% \mathscr{O}({j_{k}})\to\mathscr{O}(j)$ for $k\geq 1$, $j_{s}\geq 0$ and $j=\Sigma_{s=1}^{k}j_{s}$. The structure maps are required to be associative, unital, and equivariant in the following sense: (1) For all $c\in\mathscr{O}(k)$, $d_{s}\in\mathscr{O}({j_{s}})$, and $e_{t}\in\mathscr{O}({i_{t}})$ $\gamma(\gamma(c;d_{1},\ldots,d_{k});e_{1},\ldots,e_{j})=\gamma(c;f_{1},\ldots,% f_{k})$ where $f_{s}=\gamma(d_{s};e_{j_{1}+\ldots+j_{s-1}+1},\ldots,e_{j_{1}+\ldots+j_{s}})$ and $f_{s}=d_{s}$ if $j_{s}=0$. (2) For all $d\in\mathscr{O}(j)$ and $c\in\mathscr{O}(k)$ $\gamma(1;d)=d\text{ and }\gamma(c;1^{k})=c.$ (3) For all $c\in\mathscr{O}(k)$, $d_{s}\in\mathscr{O}({j_{s}})$, $\sigma\in\Sigma_{k}$ and $\tau_{s}\in\Sigma_{j_{s}}$ $\gamma(c\sigma;d_{1},\ldots,d_{k})=\gamma(c;d_{\sigma^{-1}1},\ldots,d_{\sigma^% {-1}k})\sigma(j_{1},...,j_{k})$ and $\gamma(c;d_{1}\tau_{1},\ldots,d_{k}\tau_{k})=\gamma(c;d_{1},\ldots,d_{k})(\tau% _{1}\oplus\ldots\oplus\tau_{k})$ where $\sigma(j_{1},\ldots,j_{k})\in\Sigma_{j}$ permutes blocks of size $j_{s}$ according to $\sigma$, and $\tau_{1}\oplus\ldots\oplus\tau_{k}$ denotes the image of $(\tau_{1},\ldots,\tau_{k})$ under the natural inclusion of $\Sigma_{j_{1}}\times\ldots\times\Sigma_{j_{k}}$ into $\Sigma_{j}$
Definition 6.1. If $\mathscr{O}$ is an operad and $(X,\ast)$ is a based simplicial set, the free $\mathscr{O}$-algebra on $X$ is ${\mathbb{O}}({X})\coloneqq\coprod_{n\geq 0}\left(\mathscr{O}(n)\times_{\Sigma_% {n}}X^{n}\right)\big{/}\sim$ where $\sim$ is a base point relation generated by $(\sigma_{i}c;x_{1},\ldots,x_{n-1})\sim(c;s_{i}(x_{1},\ldots,x_{n-1}))$ for all $c\in\mathscr{O}(n)$, $x_{i}\in X$, and $0\leq i<n$ where $\sigma_{i}c=\gamma(c,e_{i})$ with $e_{i}=(1^{i},\ast,1^{n-i-1})\in\mathscr{O}(1)^{i}\times\mathscr{O}(0)\times% \mathscr{O}(1)^{n-i-1},$ and $s_{i}(x_{1},\ldots,x_{n-1})=(x_{1},\ldots,x_{i},\ast,x_{i+1},\ldots,x_{n-1})$.
Definition 2.2. Let $(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V})$ be a torsion pair in $\mathcal{T}$ and $\mathcal{A}$ a subcategory of $\mathcal{T}$. We say that $(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V})$ is • generated by $\mathcal{A}$ if $(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V})=({}^{\perp_{0}}(\mathcal{A}^{\perp_{0}}),\mathcal{A}% ^{\perp_{0}})$; • cogenerated by $\mathcal{A}$ if $(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V})=({}^{\perp_{0}}\mathcal{A},({}^{\perp_{0}}\mathcal{A% })^{\perp_{0}})$; • compactly generated if $(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V})$ is generated by a set of compact objects. Moreover, we say that $\mathcal{A}$ generates $\mathcal{T}$ if it generates the torsion pair $(\mathcal{T},0)$ and $\mathcal{A}$ cogenerates $\mathcal{T}$ if it cogenerates the torsion pair $(0,\mathcal{T})$.
Definition 4.1. A subcategory $\mathcal{V}$ of $\mathcal{T}$ is said to be definable if there is a set of coherent functors $(F_{i})_{i\in I}$ from $\mathcal{T}$ to $\mathsf{Mod}(\mathbb{Z})$ such that $X$ lies in $\mathcal{V}$ if and only if $F_{i}(X)=0$ for all $i$ in $I$.
Definition 2.5. An object $M$ in $\mathcal{T}$ is called: • silting if $(M^{\perp_{>0}},M^{\perp_{\leq 0}})$ is a t-structure in $\mathcal{T}$ and $M\in M^{\perp_{>0}}$; • cosilting if $({}^{\perp_{\leq 0}}M,{}^{\perp_{>0}}M)$ is a t-structure in $\mathcal{T}$ and $M\in{}^{\perp_{>0}}M$. We say that two silting (respectively, cosilting) objects are equivalent, if they give rise to the same t-structure in $\mathcal{T}$ and we call such a t-structure silting (respectively, cosilting). The heart of the t-structure associated to a silting or cosilting object $M$ is denoted by $\mathcal{H}_{M}$ and the cohomological functor $\mathcal{T}\longrightarrow\mathcal{H}_{M}$ by $H^{0}_{M}$.
Definition 2.3. Two torsion pairs of the form $(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V})$ and $(\mathcal{V},\mathcal{W})$ are said to be adjacent. More precisely, we say that $(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V})$ is left adjacent to $(\mathcal{V},\mathcal{W})$ and that $(\mathcal{V},\mathcal{W})$ is right adjacent to $(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V})$. Such $\mathcal{V}$ is then called a TTF (torsion-torsion-free) class and the triple $(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V},\mathcal{W})$ is said to be a TTF triple. Moreover, a TTF triple $(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V},\mathcal{W})$ is said to be suspended (respectively, cosuspended) if the corresponding TTF class is a suspended (respectively, cosuspended) subcategory of $\mathcal{T}$.
Definition 2.1. A pair of subcategories $(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V})$ in $\mathcal{T}$ is said to be a torsion pair if (1) $\mathcal{U}$ and $\mathcal{V}$ are closed under summands; (2) $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{T}}(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V})=0$; (3) For every object $X$ of $\mathcal{T}$, there are $U$ in $\mathcal{U}$, $V$ in $\mathcal{V}$ and a triangle $U\longrightarrow X\longrightarrow V\longrightarrow U[1].$ In a torsion pair $(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V})$, the class $\mathcal{U}$ is called the aisle, the class $\mathcal{V}$ the coaisle, and $(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V})$ is said to be • nondegenerate if $\cap_{n\in\mathbb{Z}}\mathcal{U}[n]=0=\cap_{n\in\mathbb{Z}}\mathcal{V}[n]$; • a t-structure if $\mathcal{U}[1]\subseteq\mathcal{U}$, in which case we say that $\mathcal{U}[-1]\cap\mathcal{V}$ is the heart of $(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V})$; • a co-t-structure if $\mathcal{U}[-1]\subseteq\mathcal{U}$, in which case we say that $\mathcal{U}\cap\mathcal{V}[-1]$ is the coheart of $(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V})$.
Definition 2.3. Let $({\mathcal{C}},S)$ be a colored category. Cohomology $H^{*}(({\mathcal{C}},S),M)$ of $({\mathcal{C}},S)$ with coefficients in $M$, which is an object in $\mathsf{Mod}^{({\mathcal{C}},S)}$, is defined to be the right derived functor of $\text{Hom}_{\mathsf{Mod}^{({\mathcal{C}},S)}}(\underline{\mathbb{Z}},\ \ )$, namely, $H^{*}(({\mathcal{C}},S),M):=\text{Ext}_{\mathsf{Mod}^{({\mathcal{C}},S)}}^{*}(% \underline{\mathbb{Z}},M),$ where $\underline{\mathbb{Z}}$ stands for the constant sheaf with values in ${\mathbb{Z}}$.
Definition 2.6. A colored category $({\mathcal{C}},S)$ is called a naturally colored category if $f$ and $g$ are in $\sigma$ for some $\sigma\in S$, then $id_{t(f)}\sim_{S}id_{t(g)}$ and $id_{s(f)}\sim_{S}id_{s(g)}$. A naturally colored category $({\mathcal{C}},S)$ is a natural schemoid if it moreover is a schemoid; that is, $({\mathcal{C}},S)$ is endowed with the bijection (2.1) for each triple of elements in $S$.
Definition 2.1. A category $\mathcal{E}$ is said to be a (Grothendieck) topos if it satisfies the Giraud axioms (G1), (G2), (G3) and (G4) below. (G1) The category $\mathcal{E}$ has finite limits. (G2) All set-indexed sums exist in $\mathcal{E}$, and are compatible with every pullback construction. Moreover, sums are disjoint; that is, for a family $\{E_{i}\}_{i\in I}$ of objects in $\mathcal{E}$, the diagram $\xymatrix@C20pt@R20pt{0\ar[r]\ar[d]&E_{i}\ar[d]\\ E_{j}\ar[r]&\Sigma_{i\in I}E_{i}}$ is a pullback for any $i$ and $j$, where $0$ denotes the initial object. A diagram (*): $\xymatrix@C20pt@R20pt{R\ar@<0.5ex>[r]^{-}{r}\ar@<-0.5ex>[r]_{-}{s}&E\ar[r]^{f}% &F}$ in $\mathcal{E}$ is said to be exact if $f$ is the coequalizer of $r$ and $s$ and the diagram $\xymatrix@C20pt@R20pt{R\ar[r]^{s}\ar[d]_{r}&E\ar[d]^{f}\\ E\ar[r]_{f}&F}$ is a pullback. Moreover, we say that the diagram (*) above is stably exact if the exactness is preserved under every pullback construction. A monomorphism $\xymatrix@C20pt@R20pt{R\ \ \ar@{>->}[r]&E\times E}$ is said to be an equivalence relation if the induced inclusion $\text{Hom}_{\mathcal{E}}(T,R)\subset\text{Hom}_{\mathcal{E}}(T,E\times E)\cong% \text{Hom}_{\mathcal{E}}(T,E)\times\text{Hom}_{\mathcal{E}}(T,E)$ is an equivalence relation on the set $\text{Hom}_{\mathcal{E}}(T,E)$ for every object $T$. (G3) (i) For every epimorphism $E\to F$ in $\mathcal{E}$, the diagram $\xymatrix@C20pt@R20pt{E\times_{F}E\ar@<0.5ex>[r]\ar@<-0.5ex>[r]&E\ar[r]&F}$ is stably exact. (ii) For every equivalence relation $\xymatrix@C20pt@R20pt{R\ \ \ar@{>->}[r]&E\times E}$, there exists an object $E/R$ which fits into an exact diagram $\xymatrix@C20pt@R20pt{R\ar@<0.5ex>[r]\ar@<-0.5ex>[r]&E\ar[r]&E/R}$. We call a set ${\mathcal{I}}$ of objects in $\mathcal{E}$ a set of generators if for distinct morphisms $f,g:X\to Y$, there exist an object $A$ in ${\mathcal{I}}$ and a morphism $h:A\to X$ such that $f\circ h\neq g\circ h$. (G4) The category $\mathcal{E}$ has a set of generators.
Definition 1. Given a poset $\mathtt{p}$ on a finite set $N$, let $\operatorname{Int}(\mathtt{p})$ be the poset of intervals, ordered by inclusion. Then a coloring problem is a pair $(\mathtt{p},\mathtt{I})$ such that: (1) $\mathtt{p}$ is a collection of subsets of $\mathtt{I}$, ordered by inclusion. (2) $\emptyset,N\in\mathtt{p}$. (3) $\mathtt{I}$ is an order ideal of $\operatorname{Int}(\mathtt{p})$. (4) For every $S\subseteq N$, $[S,S]\in\mathtt{I}$.
Definition 3. Let $\mathtt{c}=(\mathtt{p},I)$ be a coloring problem on node set $M$, and $\mathtt{d}=(\mathtt{q},J)$ be a coloring problem on node set $N$, which is disjoint from $M$. Then their product $\mathtt{c}\cdot\mathtt{d}$ is a coloring problem on $M\cup N$, given by $\mathtt{c}\cdot\mathtt{d}=(\mathtt{p}\cdot\mathtt{q},\mathtt{I}\cdot\mathtt{J})$, where $\mathtt{p}\cdot\mathtt{q}=\{X\cup Y:X\in\mathtt{p},Y\in\mathtt{q}\}$ and $I\cdot J=\{[X\cup Y,X^{\prime}\cup Y^{\prime}]:[X,Y]\in I,[X^{\prime},Y^{% \prime}]\in J\}$.
Definition 5. Let $\mathtt{c}=(\mathtt{p},\mathtt{I})$ be a coloring problem on $N$, and let $S\subseteq N$. The restriction $\mathtt{c}|_{S}$ is non-zero if and only if $S\in\mathtt{p}$, in which case $\mathtt{c}|_{S}=(\mathtt{p}|_{S},I_{S})$, where $\mathtt{p}|_{S}=\{T\in\mathtt{p}:T\subseteq S\}$, and $I|_{S}=\{[X,Y]\in I:Y\subseteq S\}$. The contraction of $\mathtt{c}$ is non-zero if and only if $S\in\mathtt{p}$, in which case $\mathtt{c}/S=(\mathtt{p}/S,I/S)$, where $\mathtt{p}/S=\{X\subset N-S:X\cup S\in\mathtt{p}\}$, and $I/S=\{[X,Y]:X\subset Y\subset N-S,[X\cup S,Y\cup S]\in I\}$.
Definition 2. Given a coloring problem $(P,I)$ on node set $N$, the chromatic quasisymmetric function is defined by $\hat{\chi}(P,I)=\sum_{f}\prod_{n\in N}x_{f(n)}$ where we sum over all proper colorings of $(P,I)$. Likewise, the chromatic polynomial is defined by $\chi(P,I,n)=\#$ of colorings $f:N\to\{1,\ldots,n\}$. This is a polynomial function of $n$.
Definition 2.1 ([13, 5]). A semi-abelian category $\mathcal{C}$ is locally algebraically cartesian closed, or LACC, if, for every morphism $h\colon E\to B$, the corresponding change-of-base functor of the fibration of points: $h^{*}\colon Pt_{B}(\mathcal{C})\to Pt_{E}(\mathcal{C})$ has a right adjoint.
Definition 3.3 ([17]). A variety in the sense of universal algebra is a Jónsson-Tarski variety if the corresponding theory contains a unique constant $0$ and a binary operation $+$ satisfying the equalities $0+x=x+0=x$ for any $x$.
Definition 4.2. An $S$-protomodular category $\mathcal{C}$ is $S$-fibrewise algebraically cartesian closed, or $S$-FWACC, if, for every split epimorphism $h\colon E\to B$, the corresponding change-of-base functor of the fibration $S\text{-cod}$ has a right adjoint.
Definition 2.3 ([12]). A semi-abelian category $\mathcal{C}$ is algebraically coherent if, for every morphism $h\colon E\to B$, the corresponding change-of-base functor of the fibration of points preserves jointly strongly epimorphic pairs.
Definition 4.1. An $S$-protomodular category $\mathcal{C}$ is $S$-locally algebraically cartesian closed, or $S$-LACC, if, for every morphism $h\colon E\to B$, the corresponding change-of-base functor of the fibration $S\text{-cod}$: $h^{*}\colon SPt_{B}(\mathcal{C})\to SPt_{E}(\mathcal{C})$ has a right adjoint.
Definition 3.1 ([10]). A pointed, finitely complete category $\mathcal{C}$ is said to be $S$-protomodular if: (1) every point in $S$ is a strong point; (2) $SPt(\mathcal{C})$ is closed under finite limits in $Pt(\mathcal{C})$.
Definition 4.3. An $S$-protomodular category $\mathcal{C}$ is $S$-algebraically coherent if, for every morphism $h\colon E\to B$, the corresponding change-of-base functor of the fibration $S\text{-cod}$ preserves jointly strongly epimorphic pairs.
Definition 3.4 ([20, 19]). A split epimorphism $\xymatrix{A\ar@<-2pt>[r]_{f}&B\ar@<-2pt>[l]_{s}}$ in a Jónsson-Tarski variety is said to be a Schreier split epimorphism when, for any $a\in A$, there exists a unique $\alpha$ in the kernel $\text{Ker}(f)$ of $f$ such that $a=\alpha+sf(a)$.
Definition 2.2 ([5]). A semi-abelian category $\mathcal{C}$ is fibrewise algebraically cartesian closed, or FWACC, if, for every split epimorphism $h\colon E\to B$, the corresponding change-of-base functor of the fibration of points has a right adjoint.
Definition 10. Given a continuity space $(V,X,d)$, a walk $w(x_{1},x_{n})$ in $X$ and $R\subseteq V_{\prec}\times X$ we say that $R$ admits $w(x_{1},x_{n})$, and write $R\vdash(x_{1},x_{n})$, provided that for every $i\leq n-1$ we can find $(\epsilon,x_{i})\in R$ with $x_{i+1}\in B_{\epsilon}(x_{i})$ for all $i\leq n-1$.
Definition 4. Let $(X,d)$ be a $V$-space and $\epsilon\in V$ with $\epsilon\succ 0$. $B_{\epsilon}(x)=\{y\in X\mid d(y,x)\prec\epsilon\}$ is the open ball with radius $\epsilon$ about the point $x\in X$.
Definition 3. Let $V$ be a value quantale. A $V$-space is a pair $(X,d)$ with $X$ a set and $d:X\times X\to V$ such that • $d(x,x)=0$ for all $x\in X$, and • $d(x,z)\leq d(x,y)+d(y,z)$ for all $x,y,z\in X$.
Definition 2. A value distributive lattice is a completely distributive lattice $L$ for which $L_{\prec}=\{a\in L\mid a\succ 0\}$ forms a filter. A value quantale is a value distributive lattice $L$ together with an associative and commutative binary operation $+:L\times L\to L$ such that for all $x\in L$ • $x+\bot_{L}=x$, and • $\bigwedge(x+S)=x+\bigwedge S$ for all $S\subseteq L$.
Definition 3.1. We say that two arcs $(a,b),(c,d)\in\mathcal{A}$ touch if $a\leq c\leq b\leq d$ or $c\leq a\leq d\leq b$. We say that they cross if $a<c<b<d$ or $c<a<d<b$.
Definition 4.1. We call a set of arcs $\mathcal{S}\subseteq\mathcal{A}$ saturated if whenever two arcs $(a,b)$ and $(c,d)$ in $\mathcal{S}$ touch with $a\leq c\leq b\leq d$, then those of $(a,c),(c,b),(b,d)$ and $(a,d)$ that are arcs also lie in $\mathcal{S}$. We denote the collection of saturated sets of arcs in $\mathcal{A}$ by $\operatorname{Sat}(\mathcal{A})$. If $\mathcal{U}\subseteq\mathcal{A}$ is a set of arcs, we call the smallest saturated subset of $\mathcal{A}$ containing $\mathcal{U}$ the saturation of $\mathcal{U}$ and denote it by $\mathrm{sat}(\mathcal{U})$.
Definition 4.13. Let $(\mathcal{Z},<)$ be a partially ordered set. A non-crossing partition of $\mathcal{Z}$ is a partition $\mathcal{Z}=\bigsqcup_{i\in I}B_{i}$ such that if we have $a,b\in B_{i}$ and $c,d\in B_{j}$ for $i\neq j\in I$, then neither $a<c<b<d$ nor $c<a<d<b$ occurs in $\mathcal{Z}$. We denote the collection of non-crossing partitions of $\mathcal{Z}$ by $\operatorname{NC}(\mathcal{Z})$.
Definition 4.7. Let $\mathsf{T}$ be a $k$-linear triangulated category. An object $E\in\mathsf{T}$ is exceptional if $\operatorname{\mathbf{R}Hom}(E,E)\cong k,$ i.e. the derived endomorphism ring $E$ is simply $k$ concentrated in degree zero. An exceptional collection $(E_{1},\ldots,E_{n})$ in $\mathsf{T}$ is a ordered sequence of exceptional objects $E_{i}$ such that $\operatorname{\mathbf{R}Hom}(E_{j},E_{i})=0$ for $j>i$. It is strong if $\operatorname{\mathbf{R}Hom}(E_{i},E_{j})\cong\operatorname{Hom}(E_{i},E_{j})$ for $i\leq j$.
Definition 5. Let $X$ and $Y$ be two sets, and $\mathcal{R}$ and $\mathcal{R^{\prime}}$ be two relations between them. The relation $\mathcal{R}$ is said to be included in $\mathcal{R^{\prime}}$ if $x\mathcal{R}y$ implies $x\mathcal{R^{\prime}}y$, for all pairs $(x,y)\in X\times Y$.
Definition 13. Let $(N,\nu)\colon K\to K^{\prime}$ and $(N^{\prime},\nu^{\prime})\colon K\to K^{\prime}$ be PK-homographies from a relational PK-Net $K=(R,S,F,\phi)$ to a second relational PK-Net $K^{\prime}=(R,S^{\prime},F^{\prime},\phi^{\prime})$. We say that $(N,\nu)$ is included in $(N^{\prime},\nu^{\prime})$ if $\nu$ is included in $\nu^{\prime}$.
